description:
The following discussion from !46167 should be addressed:

- [ ] @markrian started a [discussion](https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/merge_requests/46167#note_444141712):  (+2 comments)

    > **thought**: We've changed the return type of this getter, using TypeScript notation, from the simple `string` to:
    > 
    > ```typescript
    > type SecuritySummaryMessage {
    >   message: string;
    >   critical?: number;
    >   high?: number;
    >   other?: number;
    > }
    > ```
    > 
    > And similarly for the `groupedTextBuilder` helper.
    > 
    > This makes me a little uneasy, since JavaScript is weakly typed, it's easy to imagine these two functions diverging in their return type in future, causing subtle breakages. 
    > 
    > Our tests are quite thorough here, though, so perhaps this is fine.

@aturinske wrote:

> I think that the best way to clean this up would be to pass the `security_summary` component all the data and let it generate the strings in there because that seems like a display concern anyways, so then these methods would go into the `security_summary` component and would not exist out here and then I do not have to worry about the type being output.

This approach would mean various utilities and getters could be removed or simplified. The component could just receive the plain counts of critical, high and other severity vulnerabilities, loading and error states, and generate the necessary message internally. Testing this would be straight-forward: given props, renders string. Some additional tests for the display/colouring logic too, but that's also simple.

